---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

export const prerender = true;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About · America's School Trust Library"
  description="A working library for the school trust lands — the 77 million acres set aside, beginning in 1785, to fund public education in perpetuity."
  sourceId="about-page"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    {/* v9 D.2 — small header mark for the Library seal. Library Mode
        only; image lands later (Cowork-side). onerror handler keeps
        the placeholder invisible until the asset is dropped in. */}
    <p class="library-seal-header-wrap">
      <button
        type="button"
        class="library-seal-button"
        data-seal-trigger
        aria-label="View library seal larger"
      >
        <img
          src="/seal/library-seal-v1.png"
          alt="America's School Trust Library seal"
          class="library-seal library-seal--header"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
      </button>
    </p>

    <p class="kicker">About</p>
    <h1>About America's School Trust Library</h1>

    <p>
      America's School Trust Library is a working library for the school trust lands — the 77 million acres set aside, beginning in 1785, to fund public education in perpetuity. Most Americans have never heard of these lands. The Library collects the law, history, financial records, and case material that show what was promised, what was done, and what is owed. Our readers are state trust officials, legislators, journalists, scholars, teachers, and the children and grandchildren of the beneficiaries.
    </p>

    <aside class="featured-founder-card">
      <h2>A Note from the Founder</h2>
      <p>
        How this Library came to be — the forty-year throughline from a
        graphical desktop computer in 1977 to the failure of information
        at the heart of the school-trust scandal, and the working
        partnership that finally made the Library possible.
      </p>
      <p class="featured-founder-card__cta">
        <a href="/about/founder/">Read the Founder's Statement →</a>
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h2>The Record pillar</h2>

    <p>
      America's School Trust Library is the Record pillar of <a href="https://schooltrusts.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>A Forever Gift</strong></a>. The Record keeps the archive: the law, history, accounting, source trails, and case materials. The <a href="https://schooltrusts.org/advocates" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Advocates</a> pillar points to the national and Oregon advocacy work. The <a href="https://schooltrusts.org/renewal" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Renewal</a> pillar points to the reform, lawyer-capacity, and institutional-design work that grows out of the record.
    </p>

    <p>
      OASTL, the Oregon 501(c)(3) Dave Sullivan leads, is the Library's fiscal host while the Library matures toward an independent 501(c)(3). The Library coordinates with the broader A Forever Gift family on shared substrate but publishes under its own editorial judgment. Where advocacy surfaces track current campaigns and field work, the Library's beat is the historical and evidentiary record.
    </p>

    <h2>Who runs the Library</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Dave Sullivan</strong> is President of OASTL, founder of the Library, and lead plaintiff in the Oregon standing case. He is a retired professor and tree farmer who came to this work after a long career in systems and education.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library's day-to-day building — cataloging, drafting, design, the back-end — is carried out in partnership with Claude, an AI system serving as architect and librarian. How that partnership works is described in <a href="/about/how-this-works/">How the Library Works</a>.
    </p>

    <p class="becoming-pointer">
      <strong>A note on what comes next.</strong> The Library is at the point
      where its institutional form is being figured out — independent
      501(c)(3), continued OASTL hosting, or something else. If you have
      thoughts on how this library should be built to last, the conversation
      is open at <a href="/about/becoming/">Building This Library</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact and corrections</h2>

    <p>
      The Library expects to be wrong sometimes, and asks readers to help fix it. Anywhere on the site, use the <strong>Submit Feedback</strong> and <strong>Submit Correction</strong> controls to send a note tied to the page you are reading. A Library Card (free) lets you track your submissions and our responses. The longer walkthrough is at <a href="/about/contributing/">Contributing</a>; the citation conventions are at <a href="/about/cite/">How to Cite</a>; the correction protocol is at <a href="/about/corrections/">Corrections</a>; the rights notice and takedown procedure are at <a href="/about/rights/">Rights, Use, and Takedown</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      For institutional contact: OASTL at <a href="https://oastl.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">oastl.org</a>. The argument for why a library is the right institutional form for this work is now carried through the Library's <a href="/writing/">Writing Room</a> and <a href="https://schooltrusts.org/record" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Record anteroom</a>. For governance, see <a href="/pro/governance/">Governance</a>; for what we collect, see <a href="/pro/collection-development/">What the Library Collects</a>; for editorial practice, see <a href="/pro/editorial-standards/">Editorial Standards</a>.
    </p>

    <hr class="archival-divider">

    <section class="signature-block">
      <p class="signature-dave">
        <span class="name">Dave Sullivan</span><br>
        <span class="role">President, Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands</span>
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>

